antine S. Rafinesque addresses three public letters to Jefferson presenting archaeological research on Kentucky's Alligewi Indians, and Jefferson circulates a Nottoway-language vocabulary. Early in 1821 he cites declining health and advanced age as he turns over the management of his Monticello and Poplar Forest plantations to his grandson Thomas Jefferson Randolph. In discussions with trusted correspondents, Jefferson admires Jesus's morality while doubting his miracles, discusses the materiality of the soul, and shares his thoughts on Unitarianism. Reflecting on the dwindling number of their old friends, he tells Maria Cosway that he is like "a solitary trunk in a desolate field, from which all it's former companions have disappeared."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aPresidentszUnited StatesvCorrespondence. 7aHISTORY / United States / 19th Century.2bisacsh  aAmerican Academy of Language and Belle Lettres.  aAmerican Indians.  aAmerican Revolution.  aAntoine Destutt de Tracy.  aArthur Spicer Brockenbrough.  aBank of the United States, Bank of Virginia.  aBenjamin Franklin.  aBernard Peyton.  aCentral College, University of Virginia.  aCollege of William and Mary.  aEdmund Bacon.  aFrancis Wayles Eppes.  aGiacomo and Michele Raggi.  aJames Breckinridge.  aJames Madison.  aJames Monroe.  aJohn Adams.  aJohn Hartwell Cocke.  aJohn Wayles Eppes.  aJoseph Carrington Cabell.  aJosé Corrêa da Serra.  aLouis Girardin.  aMarie Lafayette.  aPeter Du Ponceau.  aRichmond, Virginia.  aThomas Appleton.  aThomas Cooper.  aThomas Mann Randolph.  aU.S. Congress.  aU.S. Constitution.1 aLooney, J. Jefferson, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitl